  "prompt": "Will Northern Ireland have an independence referendum after the Brexit vote?",
  "response": "The question of whether Northern Ireland will hold an independence referendum\u2014commonly referred to as a \"border poll\" in the context of Irish reunification\u2014is a complex and politically sensitive issue, particularly in the aftermath of Brexit.\n\nUnder the **Good Friday Agreement (1998)**\u2014the peace agreement that ended decades of conflict in Northern Ireland\u2014the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland is mandated to call a border poll if it appears likely that a majority of voters would support leaving the United Kingdom and joining the Republic of Ireland. However, the threshold for such a decision is not explicitly defined, and it remains a matter of political judgment.\n\nBrexit has significantly impacted Northern Ireland's political dynamics. Following the UK's withdrawal from the EU, the Northern Ireland Protocol (later replaced by the Windsor Framework) was implemented to avoid a hard border on the island of Ireland. This arrangement has created economic and regulatory differences between Northern Ireland and the rest of the UK, which has fueled debates about Northern Ireland's constitutional future.\n\nSupport for Irish reunification has grown in some quarters, particularly among nationalist and republican communities, while unionists who wish to remain part of the UK remain a significant portion of the population. Sinn F\u00e9in, a nationalist party advocating for reunification, became the largest party in the Northern Ireland Assembly in the 2022 elections, further intensifying discussions about a potential referendum.\n\nPolitical developments in the Republic of Ireland and the UK will also influence the likelihood of a border poll. The Irish government has indicated that it would prepare for the possibility of reunification, while the UK government has expressed its commitment to the principles of the Good Friday Agreement.\n\nIn summary, while Brexit has heightened discussions about Northern Ireland's constitutional future, there is no immediate certainty about an independence referendum. Any decision to hold such a poll would depend on political, economic, and social factors, as well as the evolving will of the people of Northern Ireland.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
